AMENDED AND RESTATED PHASE I NEW HAMPSHIRE TRANSMISSION LINE SUPPORT AGREEMENT
This Amended and Restated Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement (the "Agreement"), dated as of November 1, 2020 and effective as of January 1, 2021 (the "Effective Date"), subject to the conditions precedent specified in Section 3 herein being met, is between New England Electric Transmission Corporation ("NEET") and the signatories listed in Attachment A to this Agreement (the signatories listed in Attachment A and meeting the further conditions for participation hereunder are hereinafter referred to as "Participants" or individually as a "Participant" but their rights and obligations hereunder are several and not joint as described in Section 6 hereof; NEET and the Participants are referred to herein as the "Parties" or "Party"). This Agreement amends and restates the Initial Agreement (defined below), which covered both the Phase I converter terminal facility and the Phase I New Hampshire transmission line. As of 2012, the Phase I converter terminal facility was decommissioned and only the Phase I New Hampshire transmission line (referred to hereinafter as the "Transmission Facilities") remains in the New Hampshire Phase I portion of the Interconnection. Recitals WHEREAS, the Parties were parties to the original Phase I Terminal Facility Support Agreement, which was initially entered into on December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986 (the "Initial Agreement"); WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement provides for an initial term that expires as of October 31, 2020; WHEREAS, the Initial Agreement also provides an option to the Participants to extend the Initial Agreement upon the same terms and conditions therein for up to an additional twenty years under certain conditions specified therein; WHEREAS, those conditions being met, the Participants have exercised their right to extend the Initial Agreement for an additional twenty year term and wish to make revisions to the Initial Agreement appropriate for such extension; WHEREAS, this Agreement is an integral part of a set of interrelated contracts referred to herein as the Basic Agreements that set forth the rights and obligations regarding the Interconnection; WHEREAS, the fundamental purposes of the Basic Agreements including this Agreement, are to provide for: (a) secure financial support for the costs of the Interconnection, and appropriate investment return for the owners of the assets; and (b) certain benefits to the IRH in return for their financial support for the Interconnection, including but not limited to: (i) transmission rights to the transmission transfer capability on the Interconnection between New England and Quebec up to the maximum transfer capability of 2,000 MW in accordance with Good Utility Practice; (ii) the ability to import and export energy, capacity, and ancillary services between the ISO-NE and Hydro-Quebec transmission systems for commercial and reliability purposes, promoting economic and environmental benefits to customers in New England by facilitating the delivery of zero-carbon energy at a reasonable cost; and (iii) an operable Interconnection to allow for use of the Use Rights and to promote reliability and energy security related benefits to New England; and WHEREAS, the Parties desire to amend and restate the Agreement, as amended and restated herein, effective as of January 1, 2021; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises, the execution of the other Basic Agreements hereinafter referred to, the mutual covenants hereinafter and therein set forth, and other good and valuable consideration, receipt of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: Section 1: Definitions The capitalized terms below shall have the following meanings: Advisory Committee: shall mean the Interconnection Rights Holders ("IRH") Management Committee, as provided for under the Use Agreement. Basic Agreements: shall mean the following agreements: the Support Agreements, the Equity Funding Agreements and the Use Agreement. Entitlement Transaction: shall mean any transaction utilizing the Interconnection allowed under the Use Agreement other than an Emergency Energy transaction. Equity Funding Agreements: shall mean: (1) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Electric Company, Inc., dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended; and (2) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Corporation dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended. FERC: shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Good Utility Practice: shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the New England region. Governmental Authority or Governmental Authorities: shall mean any executive, legislative, judicial, regulatory or administrative agency, body, commission, department, board, court, tribunal, arbitrating body or authority of the United States or any foreign country, or any state, local or other governmental subdivision thereof. Initial Agreement: shall have the meaning set forth in the recitals. Interconnection: shall mean the high-voltage, direct current ("HVDC") interconnection, transmission and converter terminal facilities in the United States interconnecting the Hydro-Quebec system and the ISO-NE system, provided for and described in the Basic Agreements, with a nominal transfer capability of 2,000 megawatts ("MW"). Interconnection Rights Holders ("IRH"): shall mean the parties to the Support Agreements that have the financial obligation to pay for the costs of the Interconnection in exchange for the Use Rights granted under the Support Agreements. IRH Management Committee ("IMC"): shall mean the governance committee for the IRH, as provided for under the Use Agreement, and responsible for the collective management of the IRHs' involvement in the Interconnection and the Basic Agreements. The IMC, and any successor to the IMC, is the Advisory Committee under this Agreement. ISO-NE: shall mean ISO New England Inc., the independent system operator and regional transmission organization for the New England balancing authority area, and any successor entity to ISO-NE. Participating Share: shall have the meaning provided in Section 5 of this Agreement. Phase I: shall mean the initial stage of the Interconnection in Vermont and New Hampshire, provided for and described in the Phase I Support Agreements. Phase I Support Agreements: shall mean: (i) this Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Terminal Facility Support Agreement originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986 as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986, as it may be subsequently amended. Phase I Vermont Transmission Line: shall mean the transmission facilities described in the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement and constructed in Vermont as part of Phase I of the Interconnection. Vermont Electric Transmission Company, Inc. ("VETCO") is the asset owner of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line. Phase II: shall mean the subsequent stage of construction of the Interconnection, provided for and described in the Phase II Support Agreements, that augmented the nominal transfer capability of the Interconnection to 2,000 MW through construction of an HVDC transmission line from the location of the Comerford Generating Station through New Hampshire to a new converter terminal facility adjacent to and interconnected with the Sandy Pond Substation in Ayer, Massachusetts. Phase II Support Agreements: shall mean: (i) the Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, and January 1, 1989, as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, January 1, 1989, and January 1, 1990, as it may be subsequently amended. Support Agreements: shall mean the Phase I Support Agreements and the Phase II Support Agreements, collectively. Transmission Facilities: shall mean for purposes of this Agreement the facilities described in more detail in Attachment B hereto. Use Agreement: shall mean the Fourth Amended and Restated Use Agreement, which amends and restates the Agreement with Respect to Use of Quebec Interconnection, originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated September 1, 1985, November 19, 1997, April 8, 1998, June 29, 2001 and February 11, 2002, as it may be subsequently amended. Use Rights: shall mean the exclusive rights to use the transmission capacity of the Interconnection granted to the IRH under the Support Agreements in exchange for the financial commitment of the IRH to support the full costs of the interconnection in accordance with the Support Agreements. The Use Rights are further provided for and governed by the Use Agreement. Section 2: Basic Understandings Together with this Agreement for Phase I, some or all of the Participants are also participants in the Phase II Support Agreements and the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement. Phase I of the Interconnection consists of the United States portion of a 450 kV HVDC transmission line from a terminal at the Des Cantons Substation on the Hydro-Quebec system near Sherbrooke, Quebec to the location of the former terminal having a Nominal rating of 690 MW which was adjacent to a substation at the Comerford Generating Station on the Connecticut River (hereinafter referred to as Phase I). In 2012, the Phase I Terminal Facilities were retired and the substation interconnection was decommissioned, leaving the remaining Phase I HVDC facilities and equipment to be utilized solely with Phase II. The facilities covered under the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements are integrally related and interdependent facilities, and the Parties intend that they be treated accordingly under the Basic Agreements. The Basic Agreements are intended to work together as a set of interrelated agreements governing participation in the Interconnection and the rights and obligations that result from such participation The portion of Phase II in the United States consists of an extension of the Phase I HVDC transmission line from Phase I at the Comerford Generating Station location through New Hampshire to Sandy Pond in Massachusetts with additional Terminal Facilities installed at Sandy Pond that increased the prior transfer capacity from Hydro-Quebec to approximately 2,000 MW, where conditions permit in accordance with Good Utility Practice. The Parties have made commitments under the Basic Agreements to obtain the benefits of the Interconnection, as further described in the recitals above. In connection with the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, the Parties also recognize certain other agreements and tariff provisions are important to the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. These other agreements include: (i) a certain Asset Owners Agreement between the asset owners of Interconnection facilities and the asset owners of the interconnected facilities in Quebec; (ii) the Interconnection Operators Agreement between the system operators in the United States and Quebec; (iii) the Phase II Maine Electric Power SVC Support Agreement between New England Hydro-Transmission Corp. and Maine Electric Power Company to provide for certain static var compensator facilities specified in that agreement important to the reliable operation of the Interconnection; (iv) the Transmission Service Administration Agreement among the IMC, ISO-NE and certain individual IRH (known as the Schedule 20A Service Providers) to provide for administration of transmission service over the Interconnection; (v) the HVDC Transmission Operating Agreement among the Asset Owners and ISO-NE; (vi) certain agreements related to the improvements and reinforcements to AC transmission systems in Massachusetts necessitated by Phase II, and referred to as the "Phase II New England Power AC Facilities Support Agreement" and the "Phase II Boston Edison AC Facilities Support Agreement"; and (vii) the provisions of the ISO-NE tariff and any successor provisions that provide for HQ Interconnection Capability Credits (as defined in that tariff) or similar benefits. The Parties agree to act toward these other agreements and tariff provisions in such a way as to promote the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. Transmission services over Phase I shall be on terms and conditions provided for in this Agreement, agreed upon among the Participants in the Use Agreement, and as otherwise provided for under the requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable rate schedules and transmission tariffs. Each Participant represents that it made its own independent investigations and inquiries into the projected costs and benefits of this Agreement as it deemed appropriate and did not rely upon representations (other than those contained in this Agreement) of NEET or its affiliates in deciding to enter into this Agreement. The sharing of benefits and the coordination of rights among the Participants associated with Phase I is set forth in the Use Agreement. The Use Agreement also permits each Participant to engage in Entitlement Transactions. Each Participant acknowledges that the benefits of participating in Phase I described in this Agreement and in the Use Agreement are the fundamental considerations for its signing of this Agreement and making the significant commitments to each other Participant specified herein and to the participants in the other Support Agreements. The provisions of this Agreement cover the Phase I New Hampshire transmission line (the Transmission Facilities) as described in more detail in Attachment B hereto. In accordance with the provisions hereof, NEET agrees to build upgrades to, and to own, operate, and maintain the Transmission Facilities. Each Participant hereby agrees to support the construction of upgrades to, operation, maintenance, and capital costs of, the Transmission Facilities in accordance with the provisions hereof. During the term of this Agreement, NEET shall limit its activities to those necessary or desirable consistent with Good Utility Practice in connection with Phase I unless NEET requests authority from the Advisory Committee for other activities and such authority is granted. Section 3: Conditions Precedent to Effectiveness of Amended and Restated Agreement A. General Conditions Precedent The effectiveness of this Agreement, and all rights, obligations, and performance of the signatories hereunder, are subject to (a) the Parties obtaining all necessary regulatory approvals, consents, or other actions of Governmental Authorities having jurisdiction, (b) the execution of all of the Support Agreements and the Use Agreement by the signatories thereto; and (c) the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission accepting the offer of settlement pertaining to this Agreement, including all FERC-jurisdictional contracts appended thereto, without condition or modification or with only those conditions or modifications subsequently agreed to by all the parties to that settlement. The Effective Date of this Agreement shall be on January 1, 2021, or on the date the conditions precedent specified above have been met if later. Notwithstanding anything else in this Section 3, in the event all other conditions precedent are met, the effectiveness of this Agreement shall not be delayed if one or more Participants in the States of Maine and Vermont are in the process of obtaining necessary regulatory approvals, consents, or other actions of Governmental Authorities in Maine and Vermont having jurisdiction ("Maine and Vermont Governmental Approvals"), provided that: (1) the Participants in the States of Maine and Vermont will remain subject to all terms of conditions of this Agreement while such Maine and Vermont Governmental Approvals are pending, including but not limited to the absolute and unconditional obligations of each Participant in accordance with Section 14 to make payments hereunder, and to perform and observe all other agreements on its part contained herein; and (2) in the event a Participant in the States of Maine or Vermont provides written notice to NEET that it has not obtained a necessary Maine and Vermont Governmental Approval, all rights and any obligations not incurred prior to the date of termination of such Participant under this Agreement shall be terminated as of the date of such notice and the provisions of Section 15 governing the treatment of a terminated Participant shall apply. B. Representations and Warranties of the Parties Each Party hereby represents and warrants that the following statements are true and correct as of the Effective Date: 1. General Representations and Warranties of the Parties (i) Organization; and Qualification. The Party is duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the jurisdiction of its organization and has full power and authority to own, lease and operate its assets and properties to the extent owned, leased and operated and to transact the business in which it is engaged. The Party is duly qualified or licensed to do business and is in good standing in each jurisdiction in which the property owned, leased or operated by it or the nature of the business transacted by it makes such qualification or licensure necessary, except where the failure to be so qualified or licensed or in good standing would not, individually or in the aggregate, have a material adverse effect on its assets and properties.. (ii) Authority Relative to this Agreement. The Party has full power and authority to execute, deliver and perform this Agreement and to carry out its obligations contemplated by this Agreement. The execution and delivery of this Agreement and the performance of the obligations of the Party contemplated hereby have been duly and validly authorized by all requisite corporate action, and this Agreement has been duly executed and delivered by such Party and constitutes the legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party, enforceable against the Party in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent conveyance, reorganization, moratorium, and other similar laws now or hereafter in effect affecting creditors' rights and remedies generally and subject, as to enforceability, to general principles of equity, including principles of commercial reasonableness, good faith and fair dealing (regardless of whether enforcement is sought in a proceeding at law or in equity). (iii) Consents and Approvals, No Violations. Other than as set forth in Attachment C, no declaration, authorization, consent or approval, notice to or registration or filing with any Governmental Authority is required for the execution, delivery and performance by such Party of its obligations contemplated by this Agreement. None of the execution, delivery and performance by such Party of its obligations contemplated by this Agreement conflicts with or will result in a breach or violation of such entity's organizational documents or any applicable law, rule, regulation, order or judgment, or contract, agreement or instrument by which such Party is bound or its assets affected. (iv) The execution, delivery, and performance by the Party of the Agreement do not (a) contravene the Party's charter documents, by-laws, or legislative act creating the Party, (b) to the Party's knowledge, violate any applicable law, rule, regulation, order, writ, judgment, injunction, decree, or award by which the Party is bound, (c) to the Party's knowledge, violate any indenture, instrument, agreement, or bond resolution by which the Party is bound, or (d) to the Party's knowledge, result in or require the creation or the imposition of any lien pursuant to the provisions of any indenture, instrument, agreement, or bond resolution by which the Party is bound (v) Legal Proceedings. To the Party's knowledge there are no legal or arbitral proceedings by or before any Governmental Authority, now pending or (to the actual knowledge of such Party) threatened, that if adversely determined would reasonably be expected to materially impair such Party's ability to perform its obligations contemplated by this Agreement.
2. MMWEC Representations Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Company ("MMWEC") is a Participant under this Agreement. MMWEC is a party to certain contracts, undertakings, or agreements with electric systems listed in Schedule II hereto (for these purposes including Pascoag, Rhode Island) and referred to in this Agreement as "Massachusetts Systems", and which electric systems have entered into the MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project dated as of July 15, 1982 (the "MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement"). In pertinent part, the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement imposes absolute and unconditional obligations on each Massachusetts System to: (1) pay its proportionate shares of all costs incurred by MMWEC under this Agreement; and (2) fix, revise and collect fees or charges for electric power and energy and other services sold at least sufficient to provide revenues adequate to meet its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement. MMWEC makes certain representations as set forth in this Section 3 representing unconditionally that all consents, approvals, and authorizations have been obtained by the Massachusetts Systems in connection with each such system's performance of its obligations under its MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement with MMWEC and that each such MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement imposes absolute and unconditional obligations on such systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred under this Agreement by MMWEC and has been duly authorized, executed, and delivered and is a binding commitment of such electric systems enforceable in accordance with its terms. In order that percentages of participation be consistent among the Basic Agreements, both the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and the Second MMWEC Hydro-Quebec Participation Agreement Canadian Interconnection Project Phase II (dated as of June 15, 1988, as amended, which agreement covers MMWEC's commitments for Phase II) cover the necessary commitments for each Basic Agreement. MMWEC represents and warrants to NEET and each other Party that the following statements are true and correct as of the Effective Date: (i) MMWEC has executed thirty (30) separate, but identical, MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements with each of the Massachusetts Systems dated as of July 15, 1982, as amended. (ii) The Massachusetts Systems have full power and authority to execute, deliver and perform their MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and to carry out the obligations contemplated by such MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement. The execution and delivery of the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements and the performance of the obligations of the Massachusetts Systems contemplated thereby have been duly and validly authorized by all requisite corporate action, and each of the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements has been duly executed and delivered by such Massachusetts System and constitutes the legal, valid and binding obligation of such Massachusetts System, enforceable against the Massachusetts System in accordance with its terms, subject to applicable bankruptcy, insolvency, fraudulent conveyance, reorganization, moratorium, and other similar laws now or hereafter in effect affecting creditors' rights and remedies generally and subject, as to enforceability, to general principles of equity, including principles of commercial reasonableness, good faith and fair dealing (regardless of whether enforcement is sought in a proceeding at law or in equity). (iii) The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements impose absolute and unconditional obligations on each of the Massachusetts Systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred by MMWEC under this Agreement and to fix, revise and collect fees or charges for electric power and energy and other services, facilities and commodities sold, furnished or supplied through its electric department or system at least sufficient to provide revenues adequate to meet its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement and to pay any and all other amounts payable from or constituting a charge and lien upon such revenues, including amounts sufficient to pay the principal of and interest on all bonds issued by the Massachusetts System for electric purposes. (iv) Pursuant to a Waiver and Certification executed in December 2018 ("MMWEC Participant Waiver and Certification"), each Massachusetts System has certified to MMWEC, among other things, that: a. It is a participant under a MMWEC Participation Agreement; b. It is in compliance with all of its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; c. Its obligations to make payments to MMWEC and perform its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement are absolute and unconditional; d. No assignment, transfer or sale of any interest by the Massachusetts System relieves it of any of its obligations under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; e. As necessary or advisable, MMWEC may execute and/or approve additional contracts and amendments associated with the Transmission Facilities and the Massachusetts System agrees to accept its pro rata share of the obligations and benefits of such contracts as if such contracts were originally referenced in the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement; f. All other rights and obligations of MMWEC and the Massachusetts System under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement are confirmed and acknowledged; g. The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements, and all rights and obligations thereunder, remain in full force and effect during the term of this Agreement, as may be amended and extended; and h. The Massachusetts System will provide to MMWEC any additional documents which are reasonably necessary for MMWEC's execution of additional agreements or amendments associated with this Agreement. (v) All consents, declarations, registrations, authorizations, and regulatory approvals required for MMWEC to enter into the Agreement and for MMWEC and the Massachusetts Systems to enter into the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements have been obtained and/or fulfilled. (vi) The liability of MMWEC under this Agreement is a special obligation payable solely from revenues derived by MMWEC pursuant to the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements. (vii) By a board resolution MMWEC has agreed not to grant to any other party any lien upon, pledge or assignment of revenues derived from the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements except in the case of the issuance by MMWEC of bonds, notes or other evidences of indebtedness under the terms of which proceeds of any such borrowings shall be applied to payments due to NEET and VETCO, as their interests may appear under the Support Agreements, and interest and related fees and expenses in connection with such borrowing arrangements ("MMWEC Borrowing"). The MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements provide that the monies received as payments by MMWEC under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements for support charges (as such term is defined in this Agreement) will be applied first to the payments due NEET and VETCO, as their interests may appear under the Support Agreements, and then to others; except in the event of an MMWEC Borrowing, the MMWEC Borrowing shall have the first priority for payments from revenues received by MMWEC under the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreements. C. VELCO Documentation By October 10, 2020, Vermont Electric Power Company, Inc. ("VELCO") shall provide certificates and legal opinions from counsel satisfactory to NEET, together with certified copies of related resolutions, consents, approvals, authorizations, and other documents (Documentation) necessary to establish to the satisfaction of NEET that all corporate and regulatory consents, waivers, approvals, authorizations and other actions necessary in connection with performance by such signatory of its obligations under the Agreement have been obtained and are in full force and effect, that the Agreement has been duly authorized, executed, and delivered by such signatory, and that it constitutes a binding commitment by the signatory enforceable in accordance with its terms. Prior to signing this Agreement, VELCO has provided to NEET a listing of all consents, waivers, approvals, authorizations, and other actions required for that signatory to deliver its Documentation. Since VELCO represents a number of member systems, VELCO is deemed to have signed on behalf of those systems listed in Schedule I hereto. By October 10, 2020, VELCO will provide NEET with copies of contracts with those respective systems which impose absolute and unconditional obligations on such systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred under this Agreement by VELCO. By that date, VELCO will also provide to NEET board resolutions or comparable documentation provided by those systems in form and substance satisfactory to NEET representing unconditionally that all consents, approvals, and authorizations have been obtained by its contracting systems in connection with each such system's performance of its obligations under its contract with VELCO and that each such contract imposes absolute and unconditional obligations on such systems to pay their proportionate shares of all costs incurred under this Agreement by VELCO, and has been duly authorized, executed, and delivered and is a binding commitment of such system enforceable in accordance with its terms. If regulatory approvals have not been obtained by October 1, 2020, such representations shall be conditioned upon receipt of regulatory approvals. D. Additional Terms Related to Conditions Precedent All expenses in connection with satisfying conditions precedent under this Agreement, including legal opinions where applicable, are to be borne by the signatory incurring such expense. NEET will have no responsibility for any expenses incurred by VELCO and MMWEC in satisfying conditions precedent for their respective contracting systems. (All expenses of further Documentation required for any financing by NEET with an unaffiliated third party will be borne by the Participants in the same manner). By December 2, 2020, MMWEC will provide NEET with a representative copy of the MMWEC Phase I Participation Agreement. Without limiting the foregoing, all obligations of NEET hereunder are subject to obtaining all necessary regulatory approvals authorizing NEET to charge the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge described in Section 12 hereof. Section 4: Effective Date and Term This Agreement shall become effective upon the Effective Date, as provided for in Section 3 of this Agreement. This Agreement shall expire on October 31, 2040; provided, however, that if the Transmission Facilities are operational and, at the time of such election, there are commitments to support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities for the full renewal term, a Participant shall be entitled to elect to continue participation for an additional period of up to 20 years upon the terms and conditions of this Agreement (with any amendments mutually agreed to by the Parties). Each Participant must provide notice in writing of its election to continue participation no later than by July 1, 2035 to the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall determine the length of any such extended term by August 1, 2035. The Advisory Committee must provide notice in writing no later than by November 1, 2035 to NEET of the Participant elections to continue participation and the length of such extended term. Notification will be given to each Participant by NEET of such option to continue participation by no later than May 1, 2035. NEET shall determine, in its sole discretion, whether the Participants electing to continue participation reasonably can be anticipated to support the full cost of the Transmission Facilities during the proposed extended term and shall inform each electing Participant of that determination no later than November 1, 2038. In order to inform such determination, the Participants seeking to renew shall, upon request, provide documentation that NEET may require in its discretion addressing the ability of those Participants to support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities over the proposed additional term, including but not limited to representations from all Participants and credit support from any Participants seeking to renew that are not "investment grade" Participants. It is anticipated by the Participants and NEET that during the period November 1, 2035, through November 1, 2038, NEET and the Participants electing to continue participation shall work collectively and in good faith to assist NEET in its determination. As of November 1, 2038, if the determination of NEET, in its sole discretion, is that the Participants electing to continue participation cannot support the full costs of the Transmission Facilities, NEET shall so notify all Participants stating the reasons for such determination. As a result of such determination, NEET shall be free to take any action it deems appropriate including, but not limited to termination of the Agreement as of November 1, 2040, in accordance with Section 16, restructuring of the Agreement, continuing operation of the Transmission Facilities under alternative cost recovery provisions to be approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, sale of the Transmission Facilities or any other action it deems appropriate in light of the circumstances and facts known at the time of such determination and shall notify all Participants of such proposed action on November 1, 2038. Each Participant which is also a participant under the Phase II Support Agreements or the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement shall exercise its rights and take all actions under the Phase II Support Agreements or the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement to assure that the Phase II facilities and the Vermont Phase I facilities are available to permit continued operation of Phase I for the full term of this Agreement; provided that the foregoing provision shall in no way limit the Advisory Committee's rights to act under this Agreement. Section 5: Participating Shares Each Participant shall have and be charged with a percentage interest in all of the rights and obligations hereunder (which percentage interest, as from time to time adjusted hereunder in accordance with the computation provided for in this Section 5, being hereinafter referred to as its "Participating Share"). The Participating Share of each Participant under this Agreement initially shall be in the amount set forth in the Phase I percentage interest listed on Attachment A to this Agreement. After the Effective Date of this Agreement, NEET, after consulting with the Advisory Committee, shall adjust such Participating Share amounts as of the last day of any month in which there is a change in the number of Participants or any change in the percentage interest of any Participant as herein provided, including the termination of any Participant's participation in this Agreement. NEET shall provide notice to the Advisory Committee within 60 calendar days of any such change in percentage interest. Any reallocation of Participating Shares for termination of a Participant shall be made pro rata among all remaining Participants, so as to maintain the relative proportion of Participating Shares among the remaining Participants. Section 6: Relationship among Participants The rights and obligations of the Participants hereunder are several, in accordance with their respective Participating Shares, and not joint. The rights and obligations of NEET hereunder are also several and not joint with those of the Participants or any one thereof. There is no intention to create by this Agreement, or by any grant, lease, license, or activity related hereto, an association, joint venture, trust, or partnership or to impose on NEET or any Participant trust or partnership rights or obligations; and any such implied intention is expressly negated. Except as expressly provided in this Agreement, no Participant shall have by virtue of this Agreement or of any such grant, lease, license, or activity the right or power to bind any other Participant without its express written consent. Section 7: Advisory Committee The IRH Management Committee, as provided for under the Use Agreement and acting in accordance with the governance provisions of the Use Agreement, shall be the Advisory Committee and shall approve the by-laws of the Advisory Committee. Membership in and governance of the Advisory Committee shall be in accordance with the Use Agreement. The Advisory Committee shall have the power and responsibilities set forth in this Agreement and the Use Agreement and shall adopt its own by-laws, provided that (i) voting shall be by Participating Shares at the time of the vote, (ii) a vote of two-thirds or more of Participating Shares is required to accept a NEET proposal or to take other affirmative action and a vote of more than one-third is required to reject a NEET proposal, and (iii) one or more Participants having Participating Shares of at least 10% in the aggregate may by reasonable written notice to all Participants call a meeting of the Advisory Committee. The Advisory Committee shall advise NEET on all major matters of concern to the Participants regarding the Transmission Facilities and the Interconnection. Unless time does not permit, NEET shall consult with the Advisory Committee prior to making any major decisions under this Agreement that NEET could reasonably expect to be of concern to the Participants. NEET shall follow the recommendations of the Advisory Committee to the extent reasonably practicable, unless NEET reasonably believes that such recommendations are not in accordance with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement. In addition, the Advisory Committee has authority in connection with determination of fair market value of property or property rights rented by NEET from (but not to) other utilities and termination or cancellation of construction or operation of the Transmission Facilities as specified in Sections 9, 12, and 16, respectively, of this Agreement. If NEET makes a proposal for a decision from the Advisory Committee and the Advisory Committee fails, however, to accept or reject such proposal within the later of: (i) 45 days of NEET providing the Advisory Committee with information that reasonably describes the proposal and attempts to answer questions from Participants, or (ii) a period 45 days after NEET has provided any additional information requested by the Advisory Committee, provided that in no instance shall such total period be longer than 90 days after NEET provides the Advisory Committee with notice of its proposal,, the Advisory Committee shall be deemed by NEET to have approved NEET's proposal and NEET may immediately proceed to implement its proposal. Each Participant shall be responsible for all of its expenses related to membership on the Advisory Committee. The costs of the Advisory Committee shall be treated as a Support Charge and paid for by the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge and payment provisions of this Agreement and the other Support Agreements. Section 8: Design and Construction of Upgrades to the Transmission Facilities
Except for those areas of responsibility assigned to the Advisory Committee as specified in Section 7, NEET shall be responsible for the design, engineering, procurement, installation, and all other aspects of the construction of upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, all in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objective being to achieve an appropriate balance among minimization of construction cost, minimization of operation and maintenance cost, licensing and environmental considerations, and safety and reliability of service. In carrying out these activities, NEET shall consult with the Advisory Committee in accordance with this Agreement and consistent with Good Utility Practice, and may utilize the services of its affiliates and may also select and employ a financial adviser, legal counsel, design engineering firm, a construction engineering firm, consultants, and such other firms as it considers desirable. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of NEET, such affiliate will charge on the same basis it would charge its costs to other affiliates in accordance with applicable laws and regulations. In its design and construction of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, NEET shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. NEET shall consult with the Advisory Committee concerning any major changes to the Transmission Facilities that NEET believes will have a significant effect on the Support Charges, or upon the reliability or availability of the Transmission Facilities, and shall follow the recommendations of the Advisory Committee to the extent reasonably practicable, unless NEET reasonably believes that such recommendations are not in accordance with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement; provided, however, that a failure of the Advisory Committee to provide a recommendation shall not be allowed to delay work on the Transmission Facilities to such an extent that it would have a material adverse effect on the cost of the Transmission Facilities or the time schedule for the work's completion. During the course of such work, NEET shall also furnish reports, either quarterly or monthly in NEET's sole discretion, to the Advisory Committee with respect to the progress of the work and an annual report to the Advisory Committee of actual and estimated construction expenditures for the Transmission Facilities. Section 9: Operation and Maintenance of the Transmission Facilities
Except for those areas of responsibility assigned to the Advisory Committee as specified in Section 7, NEET shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice for the benefit of all Participants, the objective being to operate the Transmission Facilities as efficiently, economically, safely, and reliably as feasible. NEET shall also use its best efforts to coordinate the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities with the operation and maintenance of the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line and the Phase II facilities. NEET shall operate and maintain the Transmission Facilities in accordance with applicable reliability criteria. In carrying out these activities, NEET may utilize the services of its affiliates and may also select and employ a financial adviser, legal counsel, consultants, and such other firms as it considers desirable. In furtherance of its responsibility, NEET may from time to time and subject to approval by the Advisory Committee, designate a company, which need not be a Participant, to operate and maintain the Transmission Facilities. To the extent services are performed by an affiliate of NEET, such affiliate will charge its costs on the same basis that it would charge to other affiliates pursuant to applicable laws and regulations. In its operation and maintenance of any upgrades to the Transmission Facilities, NEET shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, coordinate as appropriate with the other owners of the Interconnection facilities and with the owner and operator of transmission facilities interconnected to the Interconnection on the Quebec side of the border. NEET shall consult with the Advisory Committee concerning any major changes in operation and maintenance that NEET believes will have a significant effect on the cost of operating the Transmission Facilities and the Interconnection, or upon its reliability or availability, and shall follow the recommendations of the Advisory Committee to the extent reasonably practicable, unless NEET reasonably believes that such recommendations are not in accordance with Good Utility Practice or the intent of this Agreement; provided, however, that a failure of the Advisory Committee to provide a recommendation shall not be allowed to delay any repair or replacement on the Transmission Facilities. NEET shall, no less frequently than quarterly, furnish reports to the Advisory Committee with respect to the operation and maintenance of the Transmission Line and an annual report to the Advisory Committee, of estimated operation and maintenance expenses. NEET shall have no liability arising from any change in the cost estimate(s) provided hereunder. Section 10: NEET Relationship to Participants In carrying out its responsibilities hereunder, NEET agrees that it shall use its best efforts to act for the collective benefit of all Participants and NEET, to include in its contracts with independent contractors the customary provisions for assuring professional and workmanlike performance, including warranties, insurance coverage and other protections consistent with Good Utility Practice, and to enforce its rights under such contracts against the other contracting parties to the extent reasonable, reserving the discretion to settle claims on a reasonable basis. All costs of construction, including damages caused by the risks of negligence (other than gross negligence) and other risks of construction in excess of the recoveries obtained from offending parties or insurers, shall be included as part of "Investment in the Transmission Facilities" (as defined in Section 12 below) and all costs of operating the Transmission Facilities, including damages caused by risks of negligence (other than gross negligence) or other risks of operation in excess of any recoveries obtained from offending parties or insurers, shall be included in NEET's "Operating Expenses" (as defined in Section 12 below). Section 11: Transmission and Other Services In accordance with Good Utility Practice, NEET shall perform its obligations under this Agreement so as to enable the Parties to obtain the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, as described in the recitals to this Agreement. In exchange for each Participant's ongoing commitment to support the costs of the Transmission Facilities, NEET hereby grants to each Participant an exclusive right to use its Participating Share of the Transmission Facilities in accordance with the Use Agreement and applicable requirements of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and applicable rate schedules and transmission tariffs. NEET agrees that it will serve as an agent or in other similar capacity for any Participant that so requests for the buying or selling of power to be transmitted over the Transmission Facilities as an Entitlement Transaction pursuant to the terms of the Use Agreement or otherwise, provided, however, that a formal written contract with terms and conditions, including compensation for services, satisfactory to NEET is executed and delivered prior to performance of such services. Section 12: Support Charge Commencing in the month of the Effective Date and in each month thereafter, each Participant shall pay in accordance with Section 13 its Participating Share of a monthly Support Charge in an amount determined in accordance with this Section 12. The Support Charge shall be equal to NEET's Total Cost of Service Related to the Transmission Facilities for such month. The "Total Cost of Service Related to the Transmission Facilities" for any month commencing with the month in which the Effective Date occurs shall be the sum of (a) NEET's Operating Expenses for such month with respect to the Transmission Facilities, plus (b) an amount equal to one-twelfth of the Composite Percentage for such month times the Net Rate Base attributable to the Transmission Facilities. If a Support Charge payment under Section 13 is to be calculated from a date other than the first day of a month, an appropriate proration of the amount determined in (b) above shall be made for such payment only. "Uniform System" shall mean the appropriate Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) for Public Utilities and Licensees, as from time to time in effect. NEET's "Operating Expenses" shall include all amounts related to the Transmission Facilities and properly chargeable to expense accounts less any applicable credits thereto, in accordance with the Uniform System, including but not limited to operation and maintenance expense such as rent on leased property and administrative and general expenses, state and Federal income and franchise taxes, property taxes, payroll taxes, any other taxes not based on income, and depreciation and/or amortization expense; it being understood that rents on leased property shall include the rental of property or property rights related to the Transmission Facilities from New England Power Company (NEP) with rent based on fair market value as of the effective date of the rental agreement, such fair market value to be determined by NEET with the approval of the Advisory Committee which shall not be unreasonably withheld. The rental agreement between NEET and NEP referred to above will be filed with FERC and will terminate upon the termination of this Agreement. The allowance for state and federal income taxes included in Operating Expenses shall reflect the normalization of timing differences, the flow through of permanent differences between book income and tax income and amortization of excess or deficient deferred income taxes as a result of changes to federal, state or local tax rates as recorded in FERC account 411.1 or 410.1 and including tax gross up as calculated in this Attachment E. NEET, as the tax owner of the Transmission Facilities, will be entitled to the benefits and subject to the burdens of such ownership for tax purposes. NEET shall normalize investment tax credits over the depreciation or amortization period referred to in this Section 12 in accordance with the requirements of section 46(f)(1) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1954, as amended. Subject to applicable laws and regulations, NEET, to the extent it has tax losses or that it generates investment tax credits, will receive a cash payment from the National Grid system equal to the actual reduction in current tax liability, if any, resulting from the inclusion of NEET in the National Grid system consolidated tax return. NEET will receive the cash benefits only to the extent it creates savings in the consolidated tax return over the amount the taxes would have been without the inclusion of NEET. Such cash payments will be made promptly to NEET after the National Grid system receives the cash benefits from the inclusion of NEET in the consolidated return. To the extent NEET has currently received cash credit for such tax benefits, taxes in future years will be allocated to NEET despite any loss carry over credit which would have been available had NEET filed a separate return and not received the benefits currently. Taxes in future years will be allocated to NEET without regard to any loss carryover credit which would have been available had NEET filed a separate return and not received cash credit for such tax benefits currently. The "Investment in the Transmission Facilities" shall be the aggregate amount incurred at any time either before or after commercial operation of the Transmission Facilities which relates to the Transmission Facilities and is properly chargeable to NEET's utility plant accounts (including construction work in progress) in accordance with the Uniform System. In addition to the foregoing, the portion of "Investment in the Transmission Facilities" relating to AC reinforcements (as described in Attachment B hereto) shall also include all types of operating expenditures relating to such AC reinforcement (including support payments made by NEET to other utilities). "Composite Percentage" shall be computed as of the last day of each month (the "Computation Date") and with respect to any month the Composite Percentage shall be computed as of the last day of such month. "Composite Percentage" as of a Computation Date shall be the sum of (i) Return on Equity then in effect multiplied by the percentage which Equity Investment as of such date is of the Total Capital as of such date; plus (ii) the effective interest rate per annum of each principal amount of indebtedness outstanding on such date for money borrowed whether long term or short term, multiplied by the percentage which each such principal amount is of Total Capital as of such date. "Return on Equity" shall be 11.07%. "Equity Investment" as of any date shall consist of the sum of (i) all amounts theretofore paid to NEET for all capital stock theretofore issued, plus all capital contributions, less the sum of any amounts paid by NEET in the form of stock retirements, repurchases or redemptions or return of capital; plus (ii) any credit balance in the capital surplus account not included under (i) and any credit balance in the earned surplus (retained earnings) account on the books of NEET as of such date. "Total Capital" as of any date shall be calculated based on the capital structure used to determine Support Charges in accordance with this Section 12. The 'Net Rate Base' for the Transmission Facilities shall be determined as of the Effective Date and semi-annually as of June 30 and December 31 thereafter and shall consist of (i) the Investment in the Transmission Facilities, less (ii) the amount of any accumulated provision for depreciation and amortization related to Investment in the Transmission Facilities, less (iii) the amount of any reserve for deferred income taxes received by NEET, such deferred income taxes to include deferred income taxes due to accelerated depreciation and construction tax benefits related to the Transmission Facilities, less (iv) the amount of any unamortized investment tax credits received by NEET, less (or plus) (v) regulatory liabilities or assets associated with excess or deficient deferred income taxes as a result of changes in federal, state or local tax rates and other rate changes as recorded in FERC account 182.3 or FERC account 254 and including tax gross up as calculated in this Attachment E, plus (vi) such allowances related to the Transmission Facilities for materials and supplies, prepaid items, and cash working capital as may from time to time be determined by NEET as reasonably necessary and in accordance with accepted utility accounting practice. Any allowance for cash working capital shall be limited to that not sufficiently recovered through the use of estimated billing for the current month. The costs of the Advisory Committee shall be treated as a Support Charge and paid for by the Participants in accordance with the Support Charge and payment provisions of this Agreement and the other Support Agreements. Any capital upgrades to the Transmission Facilities placed in service on or after September 2020 shall be depreciated on a straight-line basis over the remaining book life of the assets in accordance with the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment D. By no later than five years from the Commission-approved Effective Date, NEET shall prepare updated depreciation studies and shall present the results of such studies to the Advisory Committee. Based on the results of those depreciation studies, NEET shall engage in good faith discussions with the Advisory Committee as to the appropriateness of NEET submitting a filing to FERC under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act to update the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment D. By no later than five years after the presentation of the most recent depreciation studies to the Advisory Committee, NEET shall request that the Advisory Committee determine, through a vote in accordance with Section 7, whether NEET shall prepare additional updated depreciation studies. If the Advisory Committee so determines, NEET shall present the results of those depreciation studies to the Advisory Committee and engage in good faith discussions with the Advisory Committee as to the appropriateness of NEET submitting a filing to FERC under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act to update the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment D. Any future changes to depreciation and/or amortization rates to be submitted for acceptance by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission shall be at a rate sufficient to recover the Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including estimated cost of removal less any salvage value which salvage value, for the purpose of calculating such depreciation and/or amortization, will not exceed the amount of cost of removal), regardless of when the upgrades are built and placed in service. In accordance with Section 4, by November 1, 2035, the Advisory Committee shall provide notice to NEET of all Participants which intend to renew participation in this Agreement for an additional renewal term of up to 20 years, as determined by the Advisory Committee no later than August 1, 2035. If the notice from the Advisory Committee does not state that a total number of Participants responsible for at least 75% of the cost responsibility for Support Charges under this Agreement intend to renew participation for the full renewal term, NEET will engage in reasonable efforts to develop and obtain FERC approval of alternative cost recovery arrangements for any portion of the Transmission Facilities that will not be fully depreciated by October 31, 2040. If FERC fails to approve such alternative cost recovery arrangements, or if FERC conditions such alternative cost recovery arrangements in a manner unacceptable to NEET, then the depreciation and/or amortization shall be modified at a rate sufficient to recover all Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including estimated cost of removal less any salvage value, which salvage value, for the purpose of calculating such depreciation and/or amortization, will not exceed the amount of cost of removal) by October 31, 2040. The capital structure used to determine Support Charges will remain at 100% equity financing until the total Net Rate Base for the Transmission Facilities that are the subject of this Agreement along with the transmission facilities that are the subject of the Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement and the transmission facilities that are the subject of the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement meets or exceeds $25 million. At that time, the Support Charges will be based on a hypothetical capital structure of 65% equity and 35% debt. The provisions establishing an 11.07% Return on Equity and addressing capital structure in the preceding paragraphs as well as the depreciation rates set forth in Attachment D shall be subject to a moratorium on any changes made or proposed by any Party under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act. The moratorium period shall commence on the filing date of Agreement with the Commission and shall end five years from the Commission-approved Effective Date. During this moratorium, no Party may propose any increase or decrease to the 11.07% Return on Equity under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act including through any Return on Equity incentive adder or through any adjustment to the Return on Equity as a result of a change in the Commission's Return on Equity policies. Section 13: Payments Commencing on or about the Effective Date and for each month thereafter, NEET shall render to each Participant an invoice for its Participating Share of the Support Charge for such month calculated on a one-month lag using actual results for such month. Unless NEET is prevented by circumstances beyond its reasonable control, NEET shall use its best efforts to render final bills within two years after the end of each calendar year based on FERC Form 1 values to true-up monthly bills for that year to actual FERC Form 1 data. NEET shall also render to each Participant an invoice or notice for its Participating Share of any amounts due under this Agreement (other than monthly Support Charge). Each Participant shall promptly pay to NEET the amount shown on any invoice submitted under this Section. NEET shall date and mail, including delivery by electronic mail, monthly invoices for the Support Charge on or about the 25th day of the month for the prior month and this invoice shall be due and payable by the 25th day of the coming month and if not paid within that time period shall bear interest compounded quarterly from the first day of the month in which payment is due to the date when payment is made at an annual rate equal to the then-applicable FERC interest rate percentage over the current interest rate on prime commercial loans from time to time in effect (the Base Rate) at the principal office of JPMorgan Chase & Co. Any invoice or notice for payments due under this Agreement (other than a monthly Support Charge invoice), that is not paid when due under this Agreement shall bear interest compounded monthly from the mailing date of the invoice to the date when payment is made at an annual rate equal to two percent (2%) over the Base Rate at the principal office of JPMorgan Chase & Co. Section 14: Character of Payment Obligations Subject to the provisions of Section 17, the obligations of each Participant to make payments hereunder, and to perform and observe all other agreements on arrangement, liquidation or similar proceedings relating to NEET, VETCO, the Phase II asset owners, the Participant, any other Participant, (ii) any failure of the Transmission Facilities to operate for any reason not resulting in cancellation of this Agreement under Section 17, (iii) any damage to or destruction of the Transmission Facilities not resulting in cancellation of this Agreement under Section 17, including but not limited to any defect in the title, quality, condition, design, operation, or fitness for use of, or any loss of use of, all or any part of the Transmission Facilities, Section 15: Default A. In the event of default by any Participant in an obligation pursuant to this Agreement, NEET or any other Participant is free to invoke such remedies at law or in equity as may be deemed appropriate. B. No delay or failure in the performance of any obligation by NEET shall be deemed to exist if it is the result of an "uncontrollable force". The term "uncontrollable force" shall be deemed to mean any cause beyond the reasonable control of NEET, which NEET could not reasonably have been expected to avoid by exercise of due diligence and foresight, including, without limiting the generality of the foregoing, storm, flood, lightning, earthquake, fire, explosion, failure of facilities not due to lack of proper care or maintenance, civil disturbance, labor disturbance, sabotage, war, national emergency, or restraint by court or public authority. In such event, NEET shall use reasonable diligence to notify the Participants of such event, to place itself in a position to fulfill its obligations hereunder, and if unable to fulfill any obligation by reason of an uncontrollable force NEET shall exercise reasonable diligence, to remove such disability with reasonable dispatch. C. In the event of (i) a Participant's failure to perform any obligation under this Agreement (other than a payment obligation under Sections 16 or 17), including a failure to make any payment to NEET within 15 days after the date of any statement rendered by NEET which failure continues for more than thirty days after written notice of such failure has been given to such Participant by NEET or, with respect to a failure to provide required VELCO documentation under Section 3, continues for more than fifteen days after written notice of a failure has been given to such Participant by NEET; or (ii) initiation of any proceeding with respect to any insolvency, bankruptcy, reorganization, or liquidation of a Participant, NEET may, in addition to any other rights or remedies that it may have against such Participant by reason thereof, terminate, as of the date of such written notice or the initiation of such proceedings, all rights of such Participant under this Agreement; provided, however, that no such termination may be made by NEET in the event of initiation of any proceeding with respect to any insolvency, bankruptcy, reorganization, or liquidation of a Participant occurring after any cancellation, termination, or permanent shutdown of the construction or operation of the Transmission Facilities. Thereupon NEET shall be entitled to receive all amounts retained or retainable from the payment agent under the Use Agreement on account of such defaulting Participant's share of benefits payable thereunder with respect to the month to which such default relates or any month prior thereto, such amount to be applied first toward the payment of the defaulted obligation hereunder with interest and the balance, if any, to be retained by NEET as liquidated damages. Upon such termination, the defaulting Participant, in addition to any other amounts owed to NEET, shall pay to NEET an amount equal to its Participating Share of the Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including any costs of removal and disposal) less any depreciation and amortization related to the Transmission Facilities to such time. NEET will first credit any such amounts received from the defaulting Participant against any payment obligations owed to NEET by the defaulting Participant and then to future payment obligations of the remaining Participants. Section 16: Termination, Suspension, Delay or Shutdown of the Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Facilities
If at any time NEET determines that continued investment in upgrades to, or operation and maintenance of the Transmission Facilities is not advisable, NEET shall consult with the Advisory Committee and, if the Advisory Committee approves, or if NEET reasonably believes and explains in writing to the Advisory Committee that Good Utility Practice so requires, NEET may delay, restrict or suspend investment in upgrades to, or operation and maintenance of, the Transmission Facilities or may shut down the Transmission Facilities for a brief or extended period or permanently. In any case in which NEET determines that safety considerations require an immediate shutdown, it shall proceed without affording to the Advisory Committee an opportunity to comment, but shall provide a report to the Advisory Committee promptly thereafter. Subject to the provisions of Section 17, if operation of the Transmission Facilities is terminated, or if the Transmission Facilities are permanently shutdown, then one of the following payments to NEET shall be made: (a) If such event or decision is approved by the Advisory Committee, each Participant shall pay to NEET within ninety days of NEET's notice of the occurrence of such event or decision its Participating Share of the Investment in the Transmission Facilities less any depreciation and amortization to such time and all costs resulting from the cancellation. Such costs shall also include the costs of the total or partial demolition and disposal of the Transmission Facilities. The Participants will be credited with any actual salvage value received by NEET including the proceeds from any sale to an affiliate of NEET. Upon termination of this Agreement, NEET retains the right to sell the Transmission Facilities at fair value to any affiliate of NEET. (b) If such event or decision is not approved by the Advisory Committee, each Participant shall pay to NEET its Participating Share of the total costs described in subparagraph (a) above within the time period specified therein. Thereupon, NEET will transfer its rights, assets, and obligations related to the Transmission Facilities to the Participants or any group thereof which they may designate. Section 17: Cancellation by Participants In the event that (i) the Transmission Facilities are damaged to the extent of being completely or substantially completely destroyed, or (ii) the Transmission Facilities are taken by exercise of the right of eminent domain or a similar right or power, then and in each such case any Participant may cancel its participation in this Agreement. Such cancellation shall be effected by written notice given by the Participant to NEET. In the event of such cancellation, all continuing obligations of the Participant hereunder, other than payment obligations with respect to periods up to the date of cancellation for which the Participant shall remain fully liable hereunder, shall cease forthwith. If at any time NEET determines that the next computation of the Participating Share allocations to be made pursuant to Section 5 could result in the Participating Share of any Participant becoming more than 50% greater than the amount of its Participating Share at the commencement of this Agreement, then prior to the date as of which such next computation would be made NEET shall give written notice of such fact to such Participant. Each such Participant shall then have the option, exercisable by written notice to NEET and all other Participants within 30 days of NEET's written notice, to elect to terminate its participation hereunder as of the date of NEET's written notice (the "effective date of termination"), provided, that such Participant within 90 days of the effective date of termination pays to NEET (i) its Participating Share (as in effect on the effective date of termination) of the Investment in the Transmission Facilities (including any costs of removal and disposal) less any depreciation and amortization related to the Transmission Facilities to the effective date of termination and (ii) all its other obligations to NEET hereunder. No termination of this Agreement shall relieve any Party of any obligation arising prior to the effective date of such termination. In addition, notwithstanding the termination of this Agreement for other purposes, this Agreement shall continue in effect to the extent necessary to provide for final billings, billing adjustments and payments. Section 18: Reserved Section 19: Miscellaneous A. Insurance. To the extent available, NEET will carry insurance to cover damage to the Transmission Facilities to the extent of the Transmission Facilities being completely or substantially destroyed. Notwithstanding the above limitation, if NEET is found by a court of competent jurisdiction to have intentionally violated this Agreement in a material manner or to have acted hereunder in a grossly negligent manner and if such court finding is final and no longer subject to appeal, then the Participants shall be entitled to recover from NEET direct damages (but not consequential or any other damages) resulting from such material intentional violation or gross negligence, unless NEET's actions or omissions have been expressly approved in advance by the Advisory Committee. In accordance with Good Utility Practice, NEET shall promptly distribute the results of each annual audit for NEET to the Advisory Committee. The books and records of NEET (including metering records) shall be open to reasonable inspection and audit by any Participant. The costs of any such additional audit, including the costs of NEET in connection with such audit, shall be borne by the Participant or Participants requesting such audit. In accordance with Good Utility Practice, NEET will promptly make any reasonable corrections necessitated as a result of the annual audit or an additional audit. D. Cost Reimbursement. In the event NEET reasonably incurs any costs not provided for elsewhere herein in connection with or as a result of planning, organizing, documenting, construction of upgrades to, suspensions, rescheduling, cancellation, operation, maintenance, shutdown, demolition, disposition, or termination of the Transmission Facilities, or otherwise arising in connection with this Agreement, each Participant shall promptly reimburse to NEET, within 30 days of the mailing date of the invoice, its Participating Share of such costs. However, NEET will endeavor to finance any additional costs, to the extent such additional costs are properly capitalizable, over the shorter of the then remaining useful life of the Transmission Facilities, the remaining term of the Agreement, or the remaining term of its permanent financing. E. Uncontrollable Force. No delay or failure in the performance of any obligation by NEET shall be deemed to exist if it is the result of an "uncontrollable force". The term "uncontrollable force" shall be deemed to mean any cause beyond the reasonable control of NEET, which NEET could not reasonably have been expected to avoid by exercise of due diligence and foresight, including, without limiting the generality of the foregoing, storm, flood, lightning, earthquake, fire, explosion, failure of facilities not due to lack of proper care or maintenance, civil disturbance, labor disturbance, sabotage, war, national emergency, or restraint by court or public authority. In such event, NEET shall use reasonable diligence to notify the Participants of such event. F. Successors and Assigns. This Agreement shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of, and may be performed by, the successors and assigns of the Parties and shall also be binding, insofar as permitted by law, on any receiver or trustee in bankruptcy, receivership, or reorganization of any Party. Except (i) for a reallocation resulting from a default as provided in Section 15, (ii) for a sale, merger, or consolidation which is approved by NEET and results in the transfer of substantially all of a Participant's assets to, and the assumption of all of the Participant's obligations hereunder by, an electric utility which is a member of the New England Power Pool, and (iii) for an assignment by NEET to a National Grid affiliate of NEET which expressly assumes NEET's rights and obligations hereunder and acquires the Transmission Facilities, and (iv) for a transfer of any or all of a Participant's Participating Share prior to the Effective Date, no assignment of this Agreement shall operate to relieve the assignor of its obligations under this Agreement without the written consent of the Parties hereto. In addition to NEET's right to assign to an affiliate, NEET may assign, without the consent of the Participants, its right, title, and interest in this Agreement, in whole or in part, and any security interests contained herein or granted hereunder, to one or more banks, investment banking firms, insurance companies, other financial institutions, or others as collateral security for NEET's obligations in connection with financing the Transmission Facilities. Written notice to all Parties will be given prior to any assignment hereunder. G. Right of Setoff. Other than any rental payments for property or property rights related to the Transmission Facilities, no Participant shall be entitled to set off against the payments required to be made by it hereunder (1) any amounts owed to it by NEET, any affiliate of NEET, or any other Participant or (2) the amount of any claim by it against NEET, any affiliate of NEET, or any other Participant. However, the foregoing shall not affect in any other way any Participant's rights and remedies with respect to any such amounts owed to it by NEET, any affiliate of NEET, or any other Participant or any such claim by it against NEET or any other Participant. NEET shall have the right to amend the provisions of Section 12 hereof from time to time by serving an appropriate statement of such amendment upon the Participants and filing the same with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (or such other regulatory agency as may have jurisdiction) in accordance with the provisions of applicable laws and any rules and regulations thereunder, and the amendment shall thereupon become effective on the date specified therein, subject to any suspension order duly issued by such agency. The Participants have the right to intervene in any regulatory proceeding brought by NEET to consider such amendment of the provisions of Section 12. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the provisions in Section 12 establishing an 11.07% Return on Equity and addressing capital structure shall be subject to a moratorium ending five years after the Effective Date, as set forth in Section 12. Any amendments changing the Participating Shares of the Participants, the rights of the Participants or a Participant as specified in Section 11, or the several nature of the obligations and rights of the Participants hereunder as specified in Section 6, shall require consent by all Parties. All other amendments to this Agreement shall be by mutual agreement of NEET and Participants owning Participating Shares aggregating at least 66 2/3%, evidenced by a written amendment signed by NEET and such Participants; and NEET and all Participants shall be bound by any such amendment. Description of the Transmission Facilities
The Transmission Facilities include a +/- 450 kV direct current transmission line from Comerford/Monroe in New Hampshire to Moore Dam in Waterford, Vermont with 3-2515 KCM ACSR conductors per pole. The Transmission Facilities cross the Connecticut River at Moore interconnecting with the VELCO system. This Interconnection is capable of transferring 2,000 MW.
